Steps:-
Deploy static-client on K8 cluster1 and static-server app on K8 cluster2 without Transparent Proxy (Note: Cluster1 is peered with Cluster2)
Deploy static-client1 on K8 cluster1 and static-server1 app on K8 cluster2 with Transparent Proxy

Exec into static-client1 pod
kubectl debug -it static-client1-9cc457699-mbwnk --image=nicolaka/netshoot -- sh

curl -s http://static-server.virtual.cluster-02.consul
"hello world from exported service"
curl -s http://static-server1.virtual.cluster-02.consul
"hello world from exported service"

dig @127.0.0.1 static-server.virtual.cluster-02.consul
dig @127.0.0.1 -p 53 static-server.virtual.cluster-02.consul
dig @127.0.0.1 -p 8600 static-server.virtual.cluster-02.consul
Note: We get same output from all the above dig command formats as it is same thing. 
Port 53: This is the standard DNS port. When you have Consul DNS enabled, the sidecar often maps port 53 to port 8600 internally (using a listener) so that standard applications (which always default to 53) can reach it.
dig defaults to port 53 if none is specified. This is identical to your first command.

nslookup -norecurse static-server.virtual.cluster-02.consul.
nslookup -norecurse static-server1.virtual.cluster-02.consul.
nslookup -norecurse static-server.virtual.cluster-02.consul. 127.0.0.1
nslookup -norecurse static-server1.virtual.cluster-02.consul. 127.0.0.1

Note: The above nslookup command with flag -norecurse and . at the end, making it absolute DNS name, resolves the DNS. If you remove . OR remove flag -norecurse, it will not work.
In a Service Mesh environment, always trust dig or curl over nslookup. nslookup is an older tool that expects a very traditional DNS setup, whereas dig accurately reports exactly what the modern sidecar is telling it.

1. The static-client (Explicit Upstreams)
In this case, Transparent Proxy logic is NOT being used for your connection. * The Path: Your application code literally says curl localhost:1234.
The Logic: Envoy is told: "Listen on port 1234. If anyone talks to that port, send them to static-server in cluster-02."
No "Hijacking": There are no iptables rules redirecting this traffic. You are manually hitting a local listener that Envoy opened specifically for you.

2. The static-client1 (Transparent Proxy Enabled)
In this case, Transparent Proxy IS being used.
The Path: Your application code says curl static-server1.virtual.cluster-02.consul.
The Logic: 1. DNS gives your app a Virtual IP (e.g., 240.0.0.5).
2. The Hijack: Your app tries to send a packet to 240.0.0.5. The iptables rules (TP) catch this packet and "hijack" it.
3. The Redirection: The packet is forcibly redirected to Envoy's universal listener on port 15001.
Automatic: You didn't have to define a local port like 1234. The mesh "intercepted" the traffic based on the destination IP.

curl works, but nslookup fails—but it is actually a classic case of how Linux resolves names differently than specialized DNS tools.

The short answer: curl is using the OS Resolver (which is being "helped" by Consul), while nslookup is a pure DNS tool that is getting tripped up by your ndots:5 setting and the "Recursion Not Available" flags.

1. Why curl works
When you run curl, the operating system looks at /etc/resolv.conf.
It asks the first server (127.0.0.1) for the name.
Even though Consul says "Recursion Not Available" for external sites, for a .consul name, it is the authority. It quickly hands the IP to the OS.
Because the OS gets a valid answer from the very first nameserver, it stops looking and gives the IP to curl.
curl connects, and you see "hello world."
2. Why nslookup fails (without -norecurse flag and trailing dot "." at the end )
nslookup (and dig) behaves differently. It doesn't just ask the OS for an answer; it tries to be "smart" about the DNS protocol.
The ndots:5 Trap: Because your name static-server1.virtual.cluster-02.consul has only 4 dots, nslookup refuses to look it up as a "real" name first.
The Search Path Loop: Instead, it tries:
static-server1.virtual.cluster-02.consul.default.svc.cluster.local
static-server1.virtual.cluster-02.consul.svc.cluster.local
...and so on.
The Conflict: * It asks 127.0.0.1 for these "long" names. Consul sees .cluster.local at the end and says: "I don't know that, and recursion is not available."
nslookup sees that "Recursion Not Available" flag and thinks: "This server is useless for this query, let me try the next one (10.11.0.10)."
10.11.0.10 (CoreDNS) doesn't know about Consul names, so it either times out or says it doesn't exist.
By the time nslookup finally tries the correct name without the suffixes, it has already been "offended" by the recursion flags or timed out waiting for CoreDNS.

The fact that curl works is the only thing that matters for your application. Your application code (Go, Python, Java, etc.) uses the same "OS Resolver" logic as curl.
The nslookup errors are just "DNS noise" caused by the specific way that tool handles the ndots configuration in Kubernetes.

Why curl works while nslookup fails (without -norecurse flag and trailing dot "." at the end )
Applications (like curl, Python, Go, or Java) use the standard system library (glibc/getaddrinfo).
The library asks 127.0.0.1 for the IP.
Consul provides the IP.
The library does not care about the recursion flag; it just sees a valid IP and hands it to curl.
curl uses the IP to connect. Success.
